Bring a large #pot{} of salted water to a boil. Once water is boiling, add
@rigatoni pasta{6%oz}; cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}.

Reserve 1 cup pasta cooking water (1 1/2 cups for 4 servings), then drain and
set aside.

Meanwhile, trim and halve @zucchini{1} lengthwise; slice crosswise into ¼-inch-thick
half-moons. Peel and mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}.

While pasta cooks, heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%tsp} in a large pan over
medium-high heat. Add zucchini; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring
occasionally, until browned and tender, ~{5-6%minutes}. Remove pan from heat;
transfer zucchini to a #plate{}.

Remove @Italian pork sausage{9%oz} from casing if necessary; discard casing. Heat
another drizzle of oil in same pan over medium-high heat. Add sausage to pan and
cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until almost cooked through, ~{3-4%minutes}
(it'll finish cooking in the next step).

Stir garlic and @tomato paste{1} into pan with sausage; cook until garlic is
fragrant, tomato paste is well distributed, and sausage is fully cooked,
~{1-2%minutes}.

> Pork Sausage is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.

Stir in @cream cheese{4%tbsp}, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, ½ cup reserved pasta
cooking water (ladle straight from the pot if pasta hasn't finished cooking yet),
@butter{1%tbsp}, @sugar{1/2%tsp}, and a pinch of @chili flakes{1%tsp} to taste.
Remove from heat.

For 4 servings, use ¾ cup pasta cooking water, 2 TBSP butter, and 1 tsp sugar.

Add drained rigatoni and zucchini to pan with sauce. Stir in half the
@Parmesan cheese{6%tbsp}. Season with salt and pepper to taste.

> TIP: If needed, stir in more reserved pasta cooking water a splash at a time
> until pasta is coated in a creamy sauce.

Divide between #bowls{}; top with remaining Parmesan and serve.